---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import BrandMark from '../components/BrandMark.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---
<BaseLayout>
  <Header>
    <BrandMark slot="mark" />
  </Header>

  <main>
    <section class="section hero-section">
      <div class="shell surface-dark pad hero-card">
        <div class="hero-copy">
          <div class="meta-label">Architecture</div>
          <h1 class="page-hero-title">Composed layers, not one monolith.</h1>
          <p class="page-copy">
            Aster separates transport, serialization, and contract into three independent layers.
            Each can be reasoned about, tested, and replaced without collapsing the others.
            The interoperability boundary lives in the shared wire behaviour.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="hero-side stack-card">
          <span>Contract</span>
          <span>Serialization</span>
          <span>Transport</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="shell surface-light-wrap">
        <div class="surface-light pad">
          <div class="section-head">
            <div>
              <div class="meta-label">Three layers</div>
               <h2 class="page-section-title">Transport, serialization, contract.</h2>
            </div>
             <p class="page-copy">
              Each layer solves one concern cleanly. The wire protocol defines the interoperability
              boundary. Language implementations keep their own native surface: Python uses decorators,
              TypeScript uses decorators, JVM languages use annotations, and other bindings follow their own idioms.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="stack-grid">
            <article class="layer transport">
              <div class="meta-label">Layer 01</div>
               <h3 class="page-card-title">iroh QUIC transport</h3>
               <p class="page-card-copy">Dial peers by ed25519 public key. iroh provides NAT traversal via hole-punching, relay fallback when direct paths fail, and multiplexed QUIC streams. Connection identity is cryptographic, not DNS-based. The transport layer handles path migration transparently.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="layer serialization">
              <div class="meta-label">Layer 02</div>
               <h3 class="page-card-title">Apache Fory serialization</h3>
               <p class="page-card-copy">Three modes for different workload shapes. XLANG mode for cross-language interop across supported bindings. NATIVE mode for single-language maximum throughput. ROW mode for zero-copy columnar access on data-heavy payloads. 10-170x faster than protobuf in Fory benchmarks.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="layer contract">
              <div class="meta-label">Layer 03</div>
               <h3 class="page-card-title">Language-native contract identity</h3>
               <p class="page-card-copy">Services are defined with language-native decorators (<code>@service</code>, <code>@rpc</code>, <code>@server_stream</code>). Contract identity is a BLAKE3 hash of the canonical form: deterministic, content-addressed, stable across languages. No IDL compiler, no generated stubs.</p>
            </article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="shell surface-dark pad">
        <div class="section-head dark">
          <div>
            <div class="meta-label">Registry / publication</div>
             <h2 class="page-section-title">Discovery without central infrastructure.</h2>
          </div>
           <p class="page-copy">
            The Aster registry is built on iroh-docs (CRDT documents), iroh-blobs (content-addressed
            storage), and iroh-gossip (pub-sub). Contract manifests are published as content-addressed
            artifacts. Endpoint capabilities are leased, not assumed. No central control plane required.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-3">
          <article class="card dark-card">
            <div class="meta-label">Publication</div>
             <h3 class="page-card-title">Content-addressed contract artifacts</h3>
             <p class="page-card-copy">Contract manifests are published to iroh-blobs with their BLAKE3 hash as the retrieval key. Any peer can fetch, verify, and cache a contract without trusting a central registry.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="card dark-card">
            <div class="meta-label">Leasing</div>
             <h3 class="page-card-title">Capability-scoped endpoint access</h3>
             <p class="page-card-copy">Endpoints advertise capabilities with ACL-controlled publishing. Access is leased with expiry rather than granted as blanket network trust.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="card dark-card">
            <div class="meta-label">Conformance</div>
             <h3 class="page-card-title">One wire protocol, native APIs everywhere</h3>
             <p class="page-card-copy">Python and TypeScript are first-class alpha bindings today. Java, .NET, Kotlin, and Go are in progress; Rust is planned. Each language keeps its own idiomatic surface while converging on the same wire framing and contract identity.</p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .pad { padding: 26px; }
  .hero-section { padding-top: 24px; }
  .hero-card, .section-head { display: grid; gap: 18px; }
  .hero-card { grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1.25fr) 260px; align-items: end; }
  .hero-copy h1 { max-width: 10ch; }
  .hero-copy p { color: var(--mist); }
  .section-head { grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1.1fr) minmax(280px, 0.9fr); margin-bottom: 22px; align-items: end; }
  .section-head p { color: var(--ink-soft); }
  .section-head.dark h2 { color: var(--cloud-strong); }
  .section-head.dark p { color: var(--mist); }
  .stack-card { display: grid; gap: 10px; }
  .stack-card span, .layer { border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: 16px 18px; }
  .stack-card span { background: rgba(255,255,255,0.06); border: 1px solid rgba(163,178,196,0.12); color: var(--cloud-strong); }
  .grid, .stack-grid { display: grid; gap: 16px; }
  .grid-3 { grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr)); }
  .stack-grid { grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr)); }
  .card { border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: 18px; }
  .dark-card { border: 1px solid rgba(163, 178, 196, 0.1); background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.025); }
  .layer { border: 1px solid rgba(25, 37, 51, 0.1); background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.72); }
  .layer.transport { box-shadow: inset 4px 0 0 var(--signal); }
  .layer.serialization { box-shadow: inset 4px 0 0 var(--relay); }
  .layer.contract { box-shadow: inset 4px 0 0 var(--trust); }
  .meta-label { margin-bottom: 10px; font-size: 11px; line-height: 1.2; letter-spacing: 0.12em; text-transform: uppercase; }
  .card h3, .layer h3 { margin: 0; }
  .dark-card h3 { color: var(--cloud-strong); }
  .layer h3 { color: var(--ink); }
  .dark-card p { color: var(--mist); }
  .layer p { color: var(--ink-soft); }
  @media (max-width: 960px) {
    .hero-card, .section-head, .grid-3, .stack-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .pad { padding: 22px; }
  }
</style>
